Stack in Java

Stack is a class in Java that represents a Last In, First Out (LIFO) data structure.

👉 This means:
the last element added is the first one to be removed

Example:

Push: 1 → 2 → 3  
Pop:  3 → 2 → 1
Important Note

Stack is based on Vector, so:

it is synchronized (thread-safe)
but considered legacy (old) in modern Java

👉 Today, Deque (like ArrayDeque) is preferred.

Creating a Stack
import java.util.Stack;

Stack<String> stack = new Stack<>();
Main Methods
push()
stack.push("Apple");
stack.push("Banana");

👉 adds element to the top

pop()
stack.pop();

👉 removes and returns the top element

peek()
stack.peek();

👉 returns top element without removing

isEmpty()
stack.isEmpty();

👉 checks if stack is empty

search()
stack.search("Apple");

👉 returns position from top (1-based), or -1

Example
Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

stack.push(1);
stack.push(2);
stack.push(3);

System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 3
System.out.println(stack.peek()); // 2
When to use Stack?

Use Stack when:

you need LIFO logic
undo/redo operations
parsing expressions
backtracking (like recursion)
Stack vs Deque (Modern Approach)
Stack	Deque (ArrayDeque)
Legacy	Modern
Synchronized	Not synchronized
Slower	Faster

👉 Preferred today:

import java.util.ArrayDeque;
import java.util.Deque;

Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
stack.push(1);
Summary
Stack follows LIFO principle
main methods: push(), pop(), peek()
thread-safe but slower
mostly replaced by Deque in modern Java

